Car Price Analysis

Karen

Background Information

A Chinese automobile company Geely Auto aspires to enter the US market by setting up their manufacturing unit there and producing cars locally to give competition to their US and European counterparts. With the data of major types of cars across the US market,this analysis may help the manufacture to made business decisions with a better understanding of what factors affect the pricing of cars. Since those may be different from the Chinese market, therefore this analysis is meaningful for Geely. They can accordingly manipulate the design of the cars to meet certain price levels. Further, the model will be a good way for management to understand the pricing dynamics of a new market.

Check normality assumption.

I checked the distribution of dependent variable, and it violates the normality assumption. This violation might attributed to the skewed nature of the dependent variable, because there are less expensive cars comparing to the medium to low level priced cars in the U.S. market.If we dont have a large sample size, then we could just interpret more carfully with the standard error and the confidence interval.


hist(Car$price)

Hypothesis Testing

The first hypothesis I want to test is the relationship between the price and the weight of automobiles. As we all know a bigger and heavier vehicle provides better crash protection than a smaller and lighter one. This could be explained by the fact that people in the heavier car are subject to less force as the heavier vehicle tends to move forward in crash with lighter vehicle. Therefore, I assume heavier automobile will be more expensive than the lighter one. To further prove my assumption, I generated the following assumption.

H0:The price and the weight of automobiles are negatively correlated or not there is not correlation between them.

H1:The price and the weight of automobiles are positively correlated.


library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

Based the above result, I could successfully reject my null hypothesis with the significant p-value and conclude that the price and the weight of automobiles are positively correlated.

Mixed Model

In the above hypothesis, we have found the positive correlation between the price and the weight of automobiles. I want to add bodytype in my model as another predictor. However, since the weight of automobile is mainly determined by the size car shell, and the bodytypes of vehicles decide the sizes of shell, its plausible that the data within each bodytype are more similar to each other than the data from different bodytype. So, I visualized the difference with each bodytype with boxplot. We could see there are some difference between each groups. This confirms that our observations from within each of the bodytype arent independent.Therefore, I use mixed model to replace the simple linear model. Mixed model is especially powerful when we want to use all of our data points and these data points are not truly independent.Even the relatively low sample size in this case will not be a problem with mixed model.


ggplot(Car, aes(carbody, price)) + 
  geom_boxplot(fill = "lightblue",alpha=0.8) + 
  theme_bw()


 Car%>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x=curbweight, y=price,color=carbody))+
  geom_point(alpha=0.6)+geom_smooth(method=lm,se=FALSE)+theme_classic() + facet_wrap(~ carbody)


library(lme4)
mixed.lmer <- lmer(price ~ curbweight + (1|carbody), data = Car)
summary(mixed.lmer)

From the result, we could find that each bodytype has price difference of 3836 dollar and the differences between carbody explain ~50% of the variance thats left over after the variance explained by our fixed effects.The mixed model improves the prediction by making predictions tighter. However, we need to pay attention to the limited data points of both convertible and hartop bodytype. Not all the random effects of these groups are significant.

Linear Regression

I randomly picked five indenpendent variables and run a correlation matrix. Since many of them have multicollinearity problem. I only picked two from them to fit the regression model. Also, before fitting the regression line, a prior power analysis is necessary to determine the sample size needed for the effect size I would expect to achieve. The result shows that 77 is a sufficient sample size. Moreover, in order to make interpretation of coefficient more meaningful, I centered each predictors. From the result, we could conclude that holding carheight at its mean level, for each units increase in horsepower, the price will go up 167.8 dollars. If we hold horsepower at its mean level, for each units increase in carheight, the price will increase 685.7 dollars.


#install.packages("PerformanceAnalytics")

centered_Mod <- Car%>%

   mutate(carheight = carheight - mean(carheight)) %>%

By checking the residuals and fitted plot, we could find a pattern and therefore we have heteroscedasticity problem. So, I used heteroscedasticity-consistent covariance matrix to test my coefficients to generate some more reasonable estimates. Also, by using heteroscedasticity-consistent covariance matrix, my standard errors are more conservative.


library(sandwich)
plot(centered_Mod)


lmtest::coeftest(centered_Mod, vcov = vcovHC)

F test

Since I would like to know if there are any difference among the front wheel drive, rear wheel drive and four wheel dirve. I conduct an anova test. Also, from the Tukey test, we could tell that the largest price difference is not between four wheel drive and other types but is between front wheel drive and front wheel drive.


anovaTest = aov(price ~ drivewheel, data = Car, projections = TRUE)
